  <div id="home">
   <div class="w3-row w3-padding-0">
    <div class="w3-twothird w3-container">
      <p> br <br> </p>
      <h1 class="w3-text-brown">Culture and Traditions</h1> 
      <p>Kadazan-Dusun culture is deeply rooted in its connection to nature and agriculture, and many of its traditions reflect this bond. The Pesta Kaamatan, or Harvest Festival, is the most prominent cultural celebration, held annually to honor the rice spirit, Huminodun. This festival includes traditional music, dance, and ceremonies led by the Bobohizan (priestess or shaman), showcasing the community's spiritual and cultural richness. It is also a time for the community to gather, give thanks, and strengthen their bonds.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="w3-third w3-container"> <div id="3.1">
      <p> br <br> </p>
      <img src="https://goingplaces.malaysiaairlines.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/Unknown-1_386_257.jpeg" alt="Kadazandusun Harvest Festival" style="width:270px;height:270px;">
    </div> 
  </div> 

  
   <div class="w3-row"> 
    <div class="w3-twothird w3-container"> 
      <h3 class="w3-text-brown">3.1</h3> 
      <p>Traditional Kadazan-Dusun attire is another hallmark of their culture. For women, the sinuangga (a black, close-fitting dress) is adorned with gold or silver thread embroidery and accessories like bead necklaces and brass belts. Men traditionally wear a gaung (shirt) paired with a siga (headcloth) to signify their identity. These attires are often worn during ceremonies and cultural events, symbolizing pride in their heritage.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="w3-third w3-container"> <div id="3.2"> 
      <img src="https://www.utusanborneo.com.my/sites/default/files/images/article/20240530/fw1389933sb0127052024kaamatan-scr.jpg" alt="Kadazan Traditional" style="width:270px;height:200px;">
    </div>
  </div>

   <div class="w3-row">                                  
 <div class="w3-twothird w3-container"> 
      <h3 class="w3-text-brown">3.2</h3> 
      <p>Music and dance are integral to Kadazan-Dusun traditions. Instruments such as the sompoton (a bamboo mouth organ), gong, and kulintangan (small brass gongs) produce melodies that accompany their traditional dances. The Sumazau, a slow and graceful dance, is the most iconic, often performed during weddings and the Harvest Festival. These art forms are passed down through generations, preserving their cultural legacy.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="w3-third w3-container"> <div id="3.3">
      <img src="https://www.mysabah.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2021/01/20210129_10.jpg" alt="Kadazandusun Traditional Instruments" style="width:270px;height:200px;">
    </div>
  </div>

      
    <div class="w3-twothird w3-container">
      <h3 class="w3-text-brown">3.3</h3> 
      <p>Oral storytelling also plays a crucial role in Kadazan-Dusun culture. Stories about ancestors, the origins of the universe, and moral lessons are shared by elders to instill cultural values in younger generations. Folk tales like the legend of Huminodun reflect their deep respect for nature and spirituality, while also serving as a medium to teach ethics and social norms.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="w3-third w3-container">
      <img src="https://hellosabah.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/2.jpg" alt="Kadazandusun" style="width:270px;height:200px;"> <div id="3.4"> 
    </div>
  </div>
 
   
    <div class="w3-twothird w3-container">
      <h3 class="w3-text-brown">3.4</h3> 
      <p>The Kadazan-Dusun continue to uphold their traditions despite modernization. Cultural initiatives, including festivals, exhibitions, and community workshops, promote these practices to both locals and visitors. By embracing modern platforms such as social media and digital archives, the community ensures that their traditions remain relevant and accessible in contemporary society.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="w3-third w3-container">
      <img src="https://diff.wikimedia.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/image_20fb26.jpeg?w=1536" alt="Kadazandusun" style="width:270px;height:210px;">
    </div>
  </div>

